old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 Monocarp is playing a computer game. Now he wants to complete the first level of this game.

A level is a rectangular grid of 2 rows and n columns. Monocarp directs a character, which begins in cell (1, 1) — at the meeting point of the 1st row and the 1st column.

Monocarp's character can move from one cell to another in one step if the cells are adjacent by side and/or corner. Formally, it is possible to move from cell (x_1, y_1) to cell (x_2, y_2) in one step if |x_1 - x_2| ≤ 1 and |y_1 - y_2| ≤ 1. Obviously, it is prohibited to go outside the grid.

There are traps in some cells. If Monocarp's character finds himself in such a cell, he dies, and the game ends.

To complete a level, Monocarp's character should reach cell (2, n) — at the intersection of row 2 and column n.

Help Monocarp determine if it is possible to complete the level.

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 100) — the number of test cases. Then the test cases follow. Each test case consists of three lines.

The first line contains a single integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 100) — the number of columns.

The next two lines describe the level. The i-th of these lines describes the i-th line of the level — the line consists of the characters '0' and '1'. The character '0' corresponds to a safe cell, the character '1' corresponds to a trap cell.

Additional constraint on the input: cells (1, 1) and (2, n) are safe.

Output

For each test case, output YES if it is possible to complete the level, and NO otherwise.

Example

Input


4
3
000
000
4
0011
1100
4
0111
1110
6

101010


Output


YES
YES
NO
YES

In the second test case, one of the possible paths is (1, 1) → (1, 2) → (2, 3) → (2, 4).

In the fourth test case, one of the possible paths is (1, 1) → (2, 2) → (1, 3) → (2, 4) → (1, 5) → (2, 6).

round:242
current node number: 204
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 You are given strings S and T, consisting of lowercase English letters. It is guaranteed that T is a permutation of the string abc. 

Find string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

A string is a permutation if the number of occurrences of each distinct character is the same in both strings. 

A string a is a subsequence of a string b if a can be obtained from b by deletion of several (possibly, zero or all) elements.

A string a is lexicographically smaller than a string b if and only if one of the following holds:

  * a is a prefix of b, but a ≠ b;
  * in the first position where a and b differ, the string a has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in b.

Input

Each test contains multiple test cases. The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases. Description of the test cases follows.

The first line of each test case contains a string S (1 ≤ |S| ≤ 100), consisting of lowercase English letters.

The second line of each test case contains a string T that is a permutation of the string abc. (Hence, |T| = 3).

Note that there is no limit on the sum of |S| across all test cases.

Output

For each test case, output a single string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

Example

Input


7
abacaba
abc
cccba
acb
dbsic
bac
abracadabra
abc
dddddddddddd
cba
bbc
abc
ac
abc


Output


aaaacbb
abccc
bcdis
aaaaacbbdrr
dddddddddddd
bbc
ac

Note

In the first test case, both aaaabbc and aaaabcb are lexicographically smaller than aaaacbb, but they contain abc as a subsequence.

In the second test case, abccc is the smallest permutation of cccba and does not contain acb as a subsequence.

In the third test case, bcdis is the smallest permutation of dbsic and does not contain bac as a subsequence.
mutated prompt:

A string is a permutation if the number of occurrences of each distinct character is the same in both strings. 

A string a is a subsequence of a string b if a can be obtained from b by deletion of several (possibly, zero or all) elements.

A string a is lexicographically smaller than a string b if and only if one of the following holds:

  * a is a prefix of b, but a ≠ b;
  * in the first position where a and b differ, the string a has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in b.

Note that there is no limit on the sum of |S| across all test cases.

Output

For each test case, output a single string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

Example

Input


7
abacaba
abc
cccba
acb
dbsic
bac
abracadabra
abc
dddddddddddd
cba
bbc
abc
ac
abc


Output


aaaacbb
abccc
bcdis
aaaaacbbdrr
dddddddddddd
bbc
ac

Note

In the first test case, both aaaabbc and aaaabcb are lexicographically smaller than aaaacbb, but they contain abc as a subsequence.

In the second test case, abccc is the smallest permutation of cccba and does not contain acb as a subsequence.

In the third test case, bcdis is the smallest permutation of dbsic and does not contain bac as a subsequence.

Monocarp's character can move from one cell to another in one step if the cells are adjacent by side and/or corner. To put it more formally, it is possible to move from cell (x_1, y_1) to cell (x_2, y_2) in one step if |x_1 - x_2| ≤ 1 and |y_1 - y_2| ≤ 1. It is clearly prohibited to go outside the grid.

There are traps in some cells, and if Monocarp's character finds himself in such a cell, he dies, and the game ends.

To complete a level, Monocarp's character should reach cell (2, n) — at the intersection of row 2 and column n.

The first line contains a single integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 100) — the number of columns.

Output

For example, imagine a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' lie in ordered alphabetical sequence; the letters 'h', 'e', 'l', and 'o' then are on the positions 8, 5, 12, and 15, respectively, so it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello." Determine how long it will take to print the word s, clearly mentioning assumptions and constraints in the solution to efficiently handle scenarios where the sequence of characters on the keyboard is given in any random order.

Input

The next 2t lines contain descriptions of the test cases.

The first line of a description contains a keyboard — a string of length 26, which consists only of lowercase Latin letters. Each of the letters from 'a' to 'z' appears exactly once on the keyboard.

The second line of the description contains the word s. The word has a length from 1 to 50 letters inclusive and consists of lowercase Latin letters.

Output

round:261
current node number: 218
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 You are given strings S and T, consisting of lowercase English letters. It is guaranteed that T is a permutation of the string abc. 

Find string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

A string is a permutation if the number of occurrences of each distinct character is the same in both strings. 

A string a is a subsequence of a string b if a can be obtained from b by deletion of several (possibly, zero or all) elements.

A string a is lexicographically smaller than a string b if and only if one of the following holds:

  * a is a prefix of b, but a ≠ b;
  * in the first position where a and b differ, the string a has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in b.

Input

Each test contains multiple test cases. The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases. Description of the test cases follows.

The first line of each test case contains a string S (1 ≤ |S| ≤ 100), consisting of lowercase English letters.

The second line of each test case contains a string T that is a permutation of the string abc. (Hence, |T| = 3).

Note that there is no limit on the sum of |S| across all test cases.

Output

For each test case, output a single string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

Example

Input


7
abacaba
abc
cccba
acb
dbsic
bac
abracadabra
abc
dddddddddddd
cba
bbc
abc
ac
abc


Output


aaaacbb
abccc
bcdis
aaaaacbbdrr
dddddddddddd
bbc
ac

Note

In the first test case, both aaaabbc and aaaabcb are lexicographically smaller than aaaacbb, but they contain abc as a subsequence.

In the second test case, abccc is the smallest permutation of cccba and does not contain acb as a subsequence.

In the third test case, bcdis is the smallest permutation of dbsic and does not contain bac as a subsequence.
mutated prompt:
You are given strings S and T, consisting of lowercase English letters. It is guaranteed that T is a permutation of the string abc. 

Find string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

A string is a permutation if the number of occurrences of each distinct character is the same in both strings, and a string a is a subsequence of a string b if a can be obtained from b by deletion of several (possibly, zero or all) elements.

A string a is lexicographically smaller than a string b if and only if one of the following holds:

  * a is a prefix of b, but a ≠ b;
  * in the first position where a and b differ, the string a has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in b.

Input

Each test contains multiple test cases. The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases. Description of the test cases follows.

The first line of each test case contains a string S (1 ≤ |S| ≤ 100), consisting of lowercase English letters.

The second line of each test case contains a string T that is a permutation of the string abc. (Hence, |T| = 3).

Note that there is no limit on the sum of |S| across all test cases.

Output

For each test case, output a single string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

Example

Input


7
abacaba
abc
cccba
acb
dbsic
bac
abracadabra
abc
dddddddddddd
cba
bbc
abc
ac
abc


Output


aaaacbb
abccc
bcdis
aaaaacbbdrr
dddddddddddd
bbc
ac

Note

In the first test case, both aaaabbc and aaaabcb are lexicographically smaller than aaaacbb, but they contain abc as a subsequence.

In the second test case, abccc is the smallest permutation of cccba and does not contain acb as a subsequence.

In the third test case, bcdis is the smallest permutation of dbsic and does not contain bac as a subsequence.

seed prompt:
 Monocarp has an array called a, which contains n integers. Let's denote k as the mathematical average of these elements (note that k may not necessarily be an integer). The mathematical mean of an array with n elements is derived by dividing the sum of the elements by the number of these elements (i.e., sum divided by n) and Monocarp wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematic mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k. Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.

Moving the hand between the keys takes time which is equal to the absolute value of the difference between positions of these keys (the keys are numbered from left to right). No time is spent on pressing the keys and on placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

Therefore, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello".

Input

  * "1 x" (1 ≤ x ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5); 
  * "2 x y" (1 ≤ x, y ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5). 



It's guaranteed that there is at least one query of the first type.

You have to perform q queries. Each query is of one of two types: 

  * "1 x" — add the element x to the end of the array, which increases the size of the array by one. 
  * "2 x y" — replace all occurrences of x in the array with y, changing all instances of the integer x in the array to y. 

Find the resulting array after performing all the queries.

Input

  * "1 x" (1 ≤ x ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5); 
  * "2 x y" (1 ≤ x, y ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5). 



It's guaranteed that there is at least one query of the first type.

seed prompt:
 Monocarp is playing a computer game. Now he wants to complete the first level of this game.

A level is a rectangular grid of 2 rows and n columns. Monocarp controls a character, which starts in cell (1, 1) — at the intersection of the 1-st row and the 1-st column.

Monocarp's character can move from one cell to another in one step if the cells are adjacent by side and/or corner. Formally, it is possible to move from cell (x_1, y_1) to cell (x_2, y_2) in one step if |x_1 - x_2| ≤ 1 and |y_1 - y_2| ≤ 1. Obviously, it is prohibited to go outside the grid.

There are traps in some cells. If Monocarp's character finds himself in such a cell, he dies, and the game ends.

To complete a level, Monocarp's character should reach cell (2, n) — at the intersection of row 2 and column n.

Help Monocarp determine if it is possible to complete the level.

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 100) — the number of test cases. Then the test cases follow. Each test case consists of three lines.

The first line contains a single integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 100) — the number of columns.

The next two lines describe the level. The i-th of these lines describes the i-th line of the level — the line consists of the characters '0' and '1'. The character '0' corresponds to a safe cell, the character '1' corresponds to a trap cell.

Additional constraint on the input: cells (1, 1) and (2, n) are safe.

Output

For each test case, output YES if it is possible to complete the level, and NO otherwise.

 Theofanis really likes sequences of positive integers, thus his teacher (Yeltsa Kcir) gave him a problem about a sequence that consists of only special numbers.

Let's define a positive number as special if it can be represented using a sum of distinct non-negative powers of n. For example, for n = 4 number 17 is special. This is because it can be written as 4^0 + 4^2 = 1 + 16 = 17, but 9 is not.

round:276
current node number: 227
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 You are given strings S and T, consisting of lowercase English letters. It is guaranteed that T is a permutation of the string abc. 

Find string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

A string is a permutation if the number of occurrences of each distinct character is the same in both strings. 

A string a is a subsequence of a string b if a can be obtained from b by deletion of several (possibly, zero or all) elements.

A string a is lexicographically smaller than a string b if and only if one of the following holds:

  * a is a prefix of b, but a ≠ b;
  * in the first position where a and b differ, the string a has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in b.

Input

Each test contains multiple test cases. The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases. Description of the test cases follows.

The first line of each test case contains a string S (1 ≤ |S| ≤ 100), consisting of lowercase English letters.

The second line of each test case contains a string T that is a permutation of the string abc. (Hence, |T| = 3).

Note that there is no limit on the sum of |S| across all test cases.

Output

For each test case, output a single string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

Example

Input


7
abacaba
abc
cccba
acb
dbsic
bac
abracadabra
abc
dddddddddddd
cba
bbc
abc
ac
abc


Output


aaaacbb
abccc
bcdis
aaaaacbbdrr
dddddddddddd
bbc
ac

Note

In the first test case, both aaaabbc and aaaabcb are lexicographically smaller than aaaacbb, but they contain abc as a subsequence.

In the second test case, abccc is the smallest permutation of cccba and does not contain acb as a subsequence.

In the third test case, bcdis is the smallest permutation of dbsic and does not contain bac as a subsequence.

round:278
current node number: 229
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 Monocarp has an array a composed of n integers, and let's represent k as the arithmetic mean of these elements (note that k might not be a whole number), and he wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematic mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k. Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k, ensuring to handle large numbers efficiently, taking into account the possible overflow in calculations.

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.
mutated prompt:
Monocarp has an array a composed of n integers, and let's represent k as the arithmetic mean of these elements (note that k might not be a whole number), and he wants to remove exactly two elements from a so that the arithmetic average of the remaining (n - 2) elements still equals k. Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k, ensuring to handle large numbers efficiently, taking into account the possible overflow in calculations.

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

seed prompt:
 Monocarp is engaged in a computer game and now he aims to accomplish the initial stage of this game.

A level is a rectangular grid of 2 rows and n columns. Monocarp controls a character, which starts in cell (1, 1) — at the intersection of the 1-st row and the 1-st column. 

Monocarp's character can move from one cell to another in one step if the cells are adjacent by side and/or corner. Formally, it is possible to move from cell (x_1, y_1) to cell (x_2, y_2) in one step if |x_1 - x_2| ≤ 1 and |y_1 - y_2| ≤ 1. Obviously, it is prohibited to go outside the grid. 

There are traps in some cells. If Monocarp's character finds himself in such a cell, he dies, and the game ends. 

To complete a level, Monocarp's character should reach cell (2, n) — at the intersection of row 2 and column n. 

Help Monocarp determine if it is possible to complete the level by considering all possible paths and accounting for the traps on the grid.

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 100) — the number of test cases. Then the test cases follow. Each test case consists of three lines.

The first line contains a single integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 100) — the number of columns.

The next two lines describe the level. The i-th of these lines describes the i-th line of the level — the line consists of the characters '0' and '1'. The character '0' corresponds to a safe cell, the character '1' corresponds to a trap cell.

Additional constraint on the input: cells (1, 1) and (2, n) are safe.

Output

For each test case, output YES if it is possible to complete the level, and NO otherwise.

 You are given a keyboard that consists of 26 keys. The keys are arranged sequentially in one row in a certain order. Each key corresponds to a unique lowercase Latin letter.

You have to type the word s on this keyboard. It also consists only of lowercase Latin letters.

To type a word, you need to type all its letters consecutively one by one. To type each letter you must position your hand exactly over the corresponding key and press it.

Moving the hand between the keys takes time which is equal to the absolute value of the difference between positions of these keys (the keys are numbered from left to right). No time is spent on pressing the keys and on placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

For example, consider a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' are arranged in consecutive alphabetical order. The letters 'h', 'e', 'l' and 'o' then are on the positions 8, 5, 12 and 15, respectively. Therefore, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello". 

Determine how long it will take to print the word s. Clearly mention assumptions and constraints in the solution.

Input

The first line contains an integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases.

The next 2t lines contain descriptions of the test cases.

The first line of a description contains a keyboard — a string of length 26, which consists only of lowercase Latin letters. Each of the letters from 'a' to 'z' appears exactly once on the keyboard.

The second line of the description contains the word s. The word has a length from 1 to 50 letters inclusive and consists of lowercase Latin letters.

Polycarp enjoys perfect squares and cubes of positive integers. Polycarp particularly appreciates numbers that are squares or cubes. Here is the beginning of the sequence of numbers he likes: 1, 4, 8, 9, ....

For a given number n, count the number of integers from 1 to n that Polycarp likes. In other words, find the number of such x that x is a square of a positive integer number or a cube of a positive integer number (or both a square and a cube simultaneously). Consider edge cases where n is very large to ensure efficient calculation. Remember to account for overlapping numbers which are both perfect squares and perfect cubes.

Input

The first line contains an integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 20) — the number of test cases.

Then t lines contain the test cases, one per line. Each of the lines contains one integer n (1 ≤ n ≤ 10^9).

Output

For each test case, print the answer you are looking for — the number of integers from 1 to n that Polycarp likes.

Example

Input


6
10
1
25
1000000000
999999999
500000000


Output


4
1
6
32591
32590
23125

round:291
current node number: 240
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 Monocarp has got an array a consisting of n integers. Let's denote k as the mathematic mean of these elements (note that it's possible that k is not an integer). 

The mathematic mean of an array of n elements is the sum of elements divided by the number of these elements (i. e. sum divided by n).

Monocarp wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematic mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k.

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.
mutated prompt:

current node number: 242
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 Mr. Chanek gives you a sequence a indexed from 1 to n. Define f(a) as the number of indices where a_i = i. 

You can pick an element from the current sequence and remove it, then concatenate the remaining elements together. For example, if you remove the 3-rd element from the sequence [4, 2, 3, 1], the resulting sequence will be [4, 2, 1]. 

You want to remove some elements from a in order to maximize f(a), using zero or more operations. Find the largest possible f(a).

Input

The first line contains one integer n (1 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the initial length of the sequence.

The second line contains n integers a_1, a_2, …, a_n (1 ≤ a_i ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the initial sequence a.

Output

Output an integer denoting the largest f(a) that can be obtained by doing zero or more operations.

Examples

Input


7
2 1 4 2 5 3 7


Output


3


Input


4
4 2 3 1


Output


2

Note

In the first example, f(A) = 3 by doing the following operations.

[2,1,4,2,5,3,7] → [2,1,2,5,3,7] → [1,2,5,3,7] → [1,2,5,3] → [1,2,3]

In the second example, f(A) = 2 and no additional operation is needed.

 Mr. Chanek gives you a sequence a indexed from 1 to n. Define f(a) as the number of indices where a_i = i. You can pick an element from the current sequence and remove it, then concatenate the remaining elements together; for example, if you remove the 3-rd element from the sequence [4, 2, 3, 1], the resulting sequence will be [4, 2, 1]. You want to remove some elements from a in order to maximize f(a), using zero or more operations. Find the largest possible f(a).

Input

The first line contains one integer n (1 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the initial length of the sequence.

The second line contains n integers a_1, a_2, …, a_n (1 ≤ a_i ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the initial sequence a.

Output

Output an integer denoting the largest f(a) that can be obtained by doing zero or more operations.

Examples

Input


7
2 1 4 2 5 3 7


Output


3


Input


4
4 2 3 1


Output


2

Note

[2,1,4,2,5,3,7] → [2,1,2,5,3,7] → [1,2,5,3,7] → [1,2,5,3] → [1,2,3]

In the second example, f(A) = 2 and no additional operation is needed.

seed prompt:
 You are given a keyboard that consists of 26 keys. The keys are arranged sequentially in one row in a certain order. Each key corresponds to a unique lowercase Latin letter. 

You have to type the word s on this keyboard. The word consists only of lowercase Latin letters. 

To type a word, you need to type all its letters consecutively one by one. To type each letter you must position your hand exactly over the corresponding key. You must then press it. 

Moving the hand between the keys takes time which is equal to the absolute value of the difference between positions of these keys (the keys are numbered from left to right). No time is spent on pressing the keys and on placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

For example, consider a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' are arranged in consecutive alphabetical order. The letters 'h', 'e', 'l' and 'o' then are on the positions 8, 5, 12 and 15, respectively. Therefore, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello". 

Determine how long it will take to print the word s. Clearly mention assumptions and constraints in the solution.

Input

The first line contains an integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases.

The next 2t lines contain descriptions of the test cases.

The first line of a description contains a keyboard — a string of length 26, which consists only of lowercase Latin letters. Each of the letters from 'a' to 'z' appears exactly once on the keyboard.

The second line of the description contains the word s. The word has a length from 1 to 50 letters inclusive and consists of lowercase Latin letters.

Output

Print t lines, each line containing the answer to the corresponding test case. The answer to the test case is the minimal time it takes to type the word s on the given keyboard.

round:300
current node number: 248
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 You are given strings S and T, consisting of lowercase English letters. It is guaranteed that T is a permutation of the string abc. 

Find string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

A string is a permutation if the number of occurrences of each distinct character is the same in both strings. 

A string a is a subsequence of a string b if a can be obtained from b by deletion of several (possibly, zero or all) elements.

A string a is lexicographically smaller than a string b if and only if one of the following holds:

  * a is a prefix of b, but a ≠ b;
  * in the first position where a and b differ, the string a has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in b.

Input

Each test contains multiple test cases. The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases. Description of the test cases follows.

The first line of each test case contains a string S (1 ≤ |S| ≤ 100), consisting of lowercase English letters.

The second line of each test case contains a string T that is a permutation of the string abc. (Hence, |T| = 3).

Note that there is no limit on the sum of |S| across all test cases.

Output

For each test case, output a single string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

Example

Input


7
abacaba
abc
cccba
acb
dbsic
bac
abracadabra
abc
dddddddddddd
cba
bbc
abc
ac
abc


Output


aaaacbb
abccc
bcdis
aaaaacbbdrr
dddddddddddd
bbc
ac

Note

In the first test case, both aaaabbc and aaaabcb are lexicographically smaller than aaaacbb, but they contain abc as a subsequence.

In the second test case, abccc is the smallest permutation of cccba and does not contain acb as a subsequence.

In the third test case, bcdis is the smallest permutation of dbsic and does not contain bac as a subsequence.
mutated prompt:

A string a is lexicographically smaller than a string b if and only if one of the following holds: * a is a prefix of b, but a ≠ b; * in the first position where a and b differ, the string a has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in b.

round:301
current node number: 249
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 Monocarp has got an array a consisting of n integers. Let's denote k as the mathematic mean of these elements; this term represents the average value of the elements. The average value of a collection of numbers is called the mean. It is important to note that it's possible that k is not an integer.

The mathematic mean of an array of n elements is the sum of elements divided by the number of these elements (i. e. sum divided by n).

Monocarp wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematic mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k.

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.

seed prompt:
 You possess an array of integers (which starts empty).

You have to perform q queries. Each query is of one of two types: 

  * "1 x" — add the element x to the end of the array; 
  * "2 x y" — replace all occurrences of x in the array with y. 

Determine the final array after all queries have been executed. Your task is to implement a function that efficiently handles these operations on the array.

Input

The first line contains a single integer q (1 ≤ q ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of queries.

Next q lines contain queries (one per line). Each query is of one of two types: 

  * "1 x" (1 ≤ x ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5); 
  * "2 x y" (1 ≤ x, y ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5). 



It's guaranteed that there is at least one query of the first type.

Output

In a single line, print k integers — the resulting array after performing all the queries, where k is the number of queries of the first type.

Examples

Input


7
1 3
1 1
2 1 2
1 2
1 1
1 2
2 1 3


Output


3 2 2 3 2 

Input


4
1 1
1 2
1 1
2 2 2


Output


1 2 1 

Input


8
2 1 4
1 1
1 4
1 2
2 2 4
2 4 3
1 2
2 2 7


Output


1 3 3 7 

Note

In the first example, the array changes as follows:

[] → [3] → [3, 1] → [3, 2] → [3, 2, 2] → [3, 2, 2, 1] → [3, 2, 2, 1, 2] → [3, 2, 2, 3, 2].

In the second example, the array changes as follows:

[] → [1] → [1, 2] → [1, 2, 1] → [1, 2, 1].

In the third example, the array changes as follows:

[] → [] → [1] → [1, 4] → [1, 4, 2] → [1, 4, 4] → [1, 3, 3] → [1, 3, 3, 2] → [1, 3, 3, 7].

It's guaranteed that there is at least one query of the first type.

seed prompt:
 You are given a keyboard that consists of 26 keys. The keys are arranged sequentially in one row in a certain order. Each key corresponds to a unique lowercase Latin letter. 

You have to type the word s on this keyboard. The word consists only of lowercase Latin letters. 

To type a word, you need to type all its letters consecutively one by one. To type each letter you must position your hand exactly over the corresponding key. You must then press it. 

Moving the hand between the keys takes time which is equal to the absolute value of the difference between positions of these keys (the keys are numbered from left to right). No time is spent on pressing the keys and on placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

For example, consider a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' are arranged in consecutive alphabetical order. The letters 'h', 'e', 'l' and 'o' then are on the positions 8, 5, 12 and 15, respectively. Therefore, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello". 

Determine how long it will take to print the word s. Clearly mention assumptions and constraints in the solution. Assume that the keyboard layout will remain constant for the entire duration of typing the word.

Input

The first line contains an integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases.

The next 2t lines contain descriptions of the test cases.

The first line of a description contains a keyboard — a string of length 26, which consists only of lowercase Latin letters. Each of the letters from 'a' to 'z' appears exactly once on the keyboard.

The second line of the description contains the word s. The word has a length from 1 to 50 letters inclusive and consists of lowercase Latin letters.

Output

round:308
current node number: 252
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 Monocarp has got an array a consisting of n integers. Let k be defined as the mathematical mean of these components; this term signifies the average value of the elements. The average value of a collection of numbers is called the mean. It is important to note that it's possible that k is not an integer.

The mathematical mean of an array of n elements is obtained by taking the total sum of the components and dividing it by the count of the components (i.e. sum divided by n).

Monocarp wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematical mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k.

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematical mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematical mean of n elements of the original array a).

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.

seed prompt:
 You have to execute q number of queries. Each query is of one of two types: 

  * "1 x" — add the element x to the end of the array. This increases the size of the array by one. Appending the element x increases the size of the array by one. Adding a new element increases the total number of items in the array.
  * "2 x y" — replace all occurrences of x in the array with y. This operation changes all instances of the integer x in the array to y. 

Find the resulting array after performing all the queries.

Input

The first line contains a single integer q (1 ≤ q ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of queries.

Next q lines contain queries (one per line). Each query is of one of two types: 

  * "1 x" (1 ≤ x ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5); 
  * "2 x y" (1 ≤ x, y ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5). 



It's guaranteed that there is at least one query of the first type.

round:315
current node number: 257
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 You are given strings S and T, consisting of lowercase English letters. It is guaranteed that T is a permutation of the string abc. 

Find string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

A string is a permutation if the number of occurrences of each distinct character is the same in both strings. 

A string a is a subsequence of a string b if a can be obtained from b by deletion of several (possibly, zero or all) elements.

A string a is lexicographically smaller than a string b if and only if one of the following holds:

  * a is a prefix of b, but a ≠ b;
  * in the first position where a and b differ, the string a has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in b.

Input

Each test contains multiple test cases. The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases. Description of the test cases follows.

The first line of each test case contains a string S (1 ≤ |S| ≤ 100), consisting of lowercase English letters.

The second line of each test case contains a string T that is a permutation of the string abc. (Hence, |T| = 3).

Note that there is no limit on the sum of |S| across all test cases.

Output

For each test case, output a single string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

Example

Input


7
abacaba
abc
cccba
acb
dbsic
bac
abracadabra
abc
dddddddddddd
cba
bbc
abc
ac
abc


Output


aaaacbb
abccc
bcdis
aaaaacbbdrr
dddddddddddd
bbc
ac

Note

In the first test case, both aaaabbc and aaaabcb are lexicographically smaller than aaaacbb, but they contain abc as a subsequence.

In the second test case, abccc is the smallest permutation of cccba and does not contain acb as a subsequence.

In the third test case, bcdis is the smallest permutation of dbsic and does not contain bac as a subsequence.

Moving the hand between the keys takes time which is equal to the absolute value of the difference between positions of these keys (the keys are numbered from left to right). No time is spent on pressing the keys and on placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

seed prompt:
 Monocarp has got an array a consisting of n integers. Let's denote k as the mathematic mean of these elements (note that it's possible that k is not an integer). 

The mathematic mean of an array of n elements is the sum of elements divided by the number of these elements (i. e. sum divided by n).

Monocarp wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematic mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k.

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.
mutated prompt:
Monocarp has got an array a consisting of n integers. Let's denote k as the mathematic mean of these elements. Please note that it's possible that k might not be an integer, but it will be a valid mathematical mean value.

The mathematic mean of an array of n elements is the sum of elements divided by the number of these elements (i. e. sum divided by n).

Monocarp wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematic mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k.

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.

 You have an array of integers (initially empty). You have to perform q queries, each query is of one of two types:

  * "1 x" — add the element x to the end of the array. The array grows by one each time you add an element;
  * "2 x y" — replace all occurrences of x in the array with y.

Input

  * "1 x" (1 ≤ x ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5); 
  * "2 x y" (1 ≤ x, y ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5). 



It's guaranteed that there is at least one query of the first type.

seed prompt:
 You are given a keyboard that consists of 26 keys. The keys are arranged sequentially in one row in a certain order. Each key corresponds to a unique lowercase Latin letter. Each key corresponds to a letter from 'a' to 'z'. 

You have to type the word s on this keyboard. The word consists only of lowercase Latin letters. 

To type a word, you need to type all its letters consecutively one by one. To type each letter you must position your hand exactly over the corresponding key. You must then press it. 

Moving the hand between the keys takes time which is equal to the absolute value of the difference between positions of these keys (the keys are numbered from left to right). No time is spent on pressing the keys and on placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

For example, consider a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' are arranged in consecutive alphabetical order. The letters 'h', 'e', 'l' and 'o' then are on the positions 8, 5, 12 and 15, respectively. Therefore, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello". 

Determine how long it will take to print the word s. Clearly mention assumptions and constraints in the solution.

Input

The first line contains an integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases.

The next 2t lines contain descriptions of the test cases.

The first line of a description contains a keyboard — a string of length 26, which consists only of lowercase Latin letters. Each of the letters from 'a' to 'z' appears exactly once on the keyboard.

The second line of the description contains the word s. The word has a length from 1 to 50 letters inclusive and consists of lowercase Latin letters.

Output

Determine the final array after all queries have been executed. Your task is to implement a function that efficiently handles these operations on the array.

Input

The first line contains a single integer q (1 ≤ q ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of queries.

Next q lines contain queries (one per line). Each query is of one of two types: 

  * "1 x" (1 ≤ x ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5); 
  * "2 x y" (1 ≤ x, y ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5). 



It's guaranteed that there is at least one query of the first type.

Output

In a single line, print k integers — the resulting array after performing all the queries, where k is the number of queries of the first type.

Examples

Input


7
1 3
1 1
2 1 2
1 2
1 1
1 2
2 1 3


Output


3 2 2 3 2 

Input


4
1 1
1 2
1 1
2 2 2


Output


1 2 1 

Input


8
2 1 4
1 1
1 4
1 2
2 2 4
2 4 3
1 2
2 2 7


Output


1 3 3 7 

Note

In the first example, the array changes as follows:

[] → [3] → [3, 1] → [3, 2] → [3, 2, 2] → [3, 2, 2, 1] → [3, 2, 2, 1, 2] → [3, 2, 2, 3, 2].

In the second example, the array changes as follows:

[] → [1] → [1, 2] → [1, 2, 1] → [1, 2, 1].

In the third example, the array changes as follows:

[] → [] → [1] → [1, 4] → [1, 4, 2] → [1, 4, 4] → [1, 3, 3] → [1, 3, 3, 2] → [1, 3, 3, 7].

round:332
current node number: 267
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 You are given strings S and T, consisting of lowercase English letters. It is guaranteed that T is a permutation of the string abc. 

Find string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

A string is a permutation if the number of occurrences of each distinct character is the same in both strings. 

A string a is a subsequence of a string b if a can be obtained from b by deletion of several (possibly, zero or all) elements.

A string a is lexicographically smaller than a string b if and only if one of the following holds:

  * a is a prefix of b, but a ≠ b;
  * in the first position where a and b differ, the string a has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in b.

Input

Each test contains multiple test cases. The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases. Description of the test cases follows.

The first line of each test case contains a string S (1 ≤ |S| ≤ 100), consisting of lowercase English letters.

The second line of each test case contains a string T that is a permutation of the string abc. (Hence, |T| = 3).

Note that there is no limit on the sum of |S| across all test cases.

Output

For each test case, output a single string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

Example

Input


7
abacaba
abc
cccba
acb
dbsic
bac
abracadabra
abc
dddddddddddd
cba
bbc
abc
ac
abc


Output


aaaacbb
abccc
bcdis
aaaaacbbdrr
dddddddddddd
bbc
ac

Note

In the first test case, both aaaabbc and aaaabcb are lexicographically smaller than aaaacbb, but they contain abc as a subsequence.

In the second test case, abccc is the smallest permutation of cccba and does not contain acb as a subsequence.

In the third test case, bcdis is the smallest permutation of dbsic and does not contain bac as a subsequence.

seed prompt:
 Monocarp has got an array a consisting of n integers. Let's denote k as the mathematic mean of these elements (note that it's possible that k is not an integer). 

The average of an array with n items is the total of its elements divided by the count of these items. This means it is equal to the total divided by n.

Monocarp wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematic mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k. 

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.

Moving the hand between the keys takes time which is equal to the absolute value of the difference between positions of these keys (the keys are numbered from left to right). No time is spent on pressing the keys and on placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

For example, consider a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' are arranged in consecutive alphabetical order. The letters 'h', 'e', 'l' and 'o' then are on the positions 8, 5, 12 and 15, respectively. Therefore, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello". 

Determine how long it will take to print the word s. Clearly mention assumptions and constraints in the solution.

Monocarp has got an array a consisting of n integers. Let's denote k as the mathematic mean of these elements. It is important to note that k might not always be an integer. However, it will be a valid mathematical mean value.

The mathematic mean of an array of n elements is the sum of elements divided by the number of these elements (i. e. sum divided by n).

Monocarp wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematic mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k.

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a). Assume the array can have elements with varying magnitudes and consider edge cases when implementing your solution.

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.

round:345
current node number: 276
old score: True ,new score: False
seed prompt:
 You are given strings S and T, consisting of lowercase English letters. It is guaranteed that T is a permutation of the string abc. 

Find string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

A string is a permutation if the number of occurrences of each distinct character is the same in both strings. 

A string a is a subsequence of a string b if a can be obtained from b by deletion of several (possibly, zero or all) elements.

A string a is lexicographically smaller than a string b if and only if one of the following holds:

  * a is a prefix of b, but a ≠ b;
  * in the first position where a and b differ, the string a has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in b.

Input

Each test contains multiple test cases. The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases. Description of the test cases follows.

The first line of each test case contains a string S (1 ≤ |S| ≤ 100), consisting of lowercase English letters.

The second line of each test case contains a string T that is a permutation of the string abc. (Hence, |T| = 3).

Note that there is no limit on the sum of |S| across all test cases.

Output

For each test case, output a single string S', the lexicographically smallest permutation of S such that T is not a subsequence of S'.

Example

Input


7
abacaba
abc
cccba
acb
dbsic
bac
abracadabra
abc
dddddddddddd
cba
bbc
abc
ac
abc


Output


aaaacbb
abccc
bcdis
aaaaacbbdrr
dddddddddddd
bbc
ac

Note

In the first test case, both aaaabbc and aaaabcb are lexicographically smaller than aaaacbb, but they contain abc as a subsequence.

In the second test case, abccc is the smallest permutation of cccba and does not contain acb as a subsequence.

In the third test case, bcdis is the smallest permutation of dbsic and does not contain bac as a subsequence.

round:348
current node number: 279
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 You have been given a keyboard with 26 keys. The keys are placed sequentially in a single row in a particular order, which remains static and does not vary for different test cases. Each key corresponds to a unique lowercase Latin letter.

You must input the word s using this keyboard. It also contains only lowercase Latin letters.

To input a word, you need to type all its letters consecutively, positioning your hand right over the correct key and pressing it.

Moving the hand between keys consumes time equal to the absolute difference of the positions between these keys (the keys are numbered from the left to the right). No time is used up pressing the keys, nor in initially placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

For instance, consider a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' are arranged in consecutive alphabetical order. The letters 'h', 'e', 'l' and 'o' are then in the positions 8, 5, 12, and 15, respectively. Thus, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello". 

Calculate how much time it will take to type the word s. Make sure assumptions and constraints are clearly mentioned in the solution. Assume that the arrangement of the keys on the keyboard remains fixed between different test cases. You can consider that the word s is non-empty and its maximum length is 10^5 characters.

Input

The first line contains an integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases.

The next 2t lines contain descriptions of the test cases.

The first line of a description contains a keyboard — a string of length 26, which consists only of lowercase Latin letters. Each of the letters from 'a' to 'z' appears exactly once on the keyboard.

The second line of the description contains the word s. The word has a length from 1 to 50 letters inclusive and consists of lowercase Latin letters.

Output

Print t lines, each line containing the answer to the corresponding test case. The answer to the test case is the minimal time it takes to type the word s on the given keyboard.

You have been given a keyboard with 26 keys. The keys are placed sequentially in a single row in a particular order, which remains static and does not vary for different test cases. Each key corresponds to a unique lowercase Latin letter.

You need to enter the word s using this keyboard. It includes only lowercase Latin letters. 

To enter a word, you need to type all its letters consecutively, positioning your hand right over the correct key and pressing it.

Moving the hand between keys consumes time equal to the absolute difference of the positions between these keys (the keys are numbered from the left to the right). No time is used up pressing the keys, nor in initially placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

For instance, consider a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' are arranged in consecutive alphabetical order. The letters 'h', 'e', 'l' and 'o' are then in the positions 8, 5, 12, and 15, respectively. Thus, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello". 

Determine the amount of time needed to type the word s. Make sure assumptions and constraints are clearly mentioned in the solution. Assume that the arrangement of the keys on the keyboard remains fixed between different test cases. You can consider that the word s is non-empty and its maximum length is 10^5 characters.

seed prompt:
 Monocarp has obtained an array a composed of n integers. Let's denote k as the average of these elements. It is important to note that k might not always be an integer. However, it will be a valid mathematical mean value.

To find the mean of an array with n elements, you take their total sum and divide by the number of these elements (i. e. sum divided by n).

Monocarp wants to remove exactly two elements from a so that the mathematical average of the remaining (n - 2) elements still equals k.

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are removed, the mathematical average of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the average of n elements of the original array a). Assume the array can have elements with varying magnitudes and consider edge cases when implementing your solution.

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.

seed prompt:
 Monocarp has got an array a consisting of n integers. Let's denote k as the mean of these elements (note that k might not be an integer).

The average of an array with n items is the total of its elements divided by the count of these items. This means it is equal to the total divided by n.

Monocarp wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematic mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k.

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.

seed prompt:
 You are given a keyboard that consists of 26 keys. The keys are arranged sequentially in one row in a certain order. Each key corresponds to a unique lowercase Latin letter. 

You have to type the word s on this keyboard. The word consists only of lowercase Latin letters. 

To type a word, you need to type all its letters consecutively one by one. To type each letter you must position your hand exactly over the corresponding key. You must then press it. 

Moving the hand between the keys takes time which is equal to the absolute value of the difference between positions of these keys (the keys are numbered from left to right). No time is spent on pressing the keys and on placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

For example, consider a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' are arranged in consecutive alphabetical order. The letters 'h', 'e', 'l' and 'o' then are on the positions 8, 5, 12 and 15, respectively. Therefore, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello". 

Determine how long it will take to print the word s. Clearly mention assumptions and constraints in the solution. Assume that the keyboard layout will remain constant for the entire duration of typing the word.

Input

The first line contains an integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases.

The next 2t lines contain descriptions of the test cases.

The first line of a description contains a keyboard — a string of length 26, which consists only of lowercase Latin letters. Each of the letters from 'a' to 'z' appears exactly once on the keyboard.

The second line of the description contains the word s. The word has a length from 1 to 50 letters inclusive and consists of lowercase Latin letters.

Output

  * "1 x" — add the element x to the end of the array, which increases the size of the array by one. 
  * "2 x y" — replace all occurrences of x in the array with y, changing all instances of the integer x in the array to y. 

Find the resulting array after performing all the queries.

Input

The first line contains a single integer q (1 ≤ q ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of queries.

Next q lines contain queries (one per line). Each query is of one of two types: 

  * "1 x" (1 ≤ x ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5); 
  * "2 x y" (1 ≤ x, y ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5). 



It's guaranteed that there is at least one query of the first type.

Output

The first line contains one integer n (1 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the initial length of the sequence.

The second line contains n integers a_1, a_2, …, a_n (1 ≤ a_i ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the initial sequence a.

Output

Output an integer denoting the largest f(a) that can be obtained by doing zero or more operations.

Examples

Input


7
2 1 4 2 5 3 7


Output


3


Input


4
4 2 3 1


Output


2

Note

In the first example, f(A) = 3 by doing the following operations.

[2,1,4,2,5,3,7] → [2,1,2,5,3,7] → [1,2,5,3,7] → [1,2,5,3] → [1,2,3]

In the second example, f(A) = 2 and no additional operation is needed.

seed prompt:
 Monocarp has obtained an array a composed of n integers. Let's denote k as the average of these elements. It is important to note that k might not always be an integer. However, it will be a valid mathematical mean value, which means it's the result of summing the elements and dividing by their count. 

To find the mean of an array with n elements, you take their total sum and divide by the number of these elements (i. e. sum divided by n).

Monocarp wants to remove exactly two elements from a so that the mathematical average of the remaining (n - 2) elements still equals k.

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are removed, the mathematical average of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the average of n elements of the original array a). Assume the array can have elements with varying magnitudes and consider edge cases when implementing your solution.

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.

 You possess an array of integers (which starts empty).

You have to perform q queries. Each query is of one of two types: 

  * "1 x" — add the element x to the end of the array; 
  * "2 x y" — replace all occurrences of x in the array with y. 

Determine the final array after all queries have been executed. Your task is to implement a function that efficiently handles these operations on the array.

Input

The first line contains a single integer q (1 ≤ q ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of queries.

  * "1 x" (1 ≤ x ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5); 
  * "2 x y" (1 ≤ x, y ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5). 



It's guaranteed that there is at least one query of the first type.

seed prompt:
 You are given a keyboard that consists of 26 keys. The keys are arranged sequentially in one row in a certain order. Each key corresponds to a unique lowercase Latin letter. Each key corresponds to a letter from 'a' to 'z'. 

You have to type the word s on this keyboard. The word consists only of lowercase Latin letters. 

To type a word, you need to type all its letters consecutively one by one. To type each letter you must position your hand exactly over the corresponding key. You must then press it. 

Moving the hand between the keys takes time which is equal to the absolute value of the difference between positions of these keys (the keys are numbered from left to right). No time is spent on pressing the keys and on placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

For example, consider a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' are arranged in consecutive alphabetical order. The letters 'h', 'e', 'l' and 'o' then are on the positions 8, 5, 12 and 15, respectively. Therefore, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello". 

Determine how long it will take to print the word s. Clearly mention assumptions and constraints in the solution. Ensure that the keyboard layout does not change during the operation.

Input

The first line contains an integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases.

The next 2t lines contain descriptions of the test cases.

The first line of a description contains a keyboard — a string of length 26, which consists only of lowercase Latin letters. Each of the letters from 'a' to 'z' appears exactly once on the keyboard.

The second line of the description contains the word s. The word has a length from 1 to 50 letters inclusive and consists of lowercase Latin letters.

Output

Print t lines, each line containing the answer to the corresponding test case. The answer to the test case is the minimal time it takes to type the word s on the given keyboard.

round:374
current node number: 300
old score: True ,new score: True
seed prompt:
 Monocarp has got an array a consisting of n integers. Let's denote k as the mathematic mean of these elements (note that it's possible that k is not an integer). 

The average of an array with n items is the total of its elements divided by the count of these items (i.e., total divided by n).

Monocarp wants to delete exactly two elements from a so that the mathematic mean of the remaining (n - 2) elements is still equal to k.

Your task is to calculate the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Input

The first line contains a single integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 10^4) — the number of testcases.

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

The second line contains a sequence of integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_n (0 ≤ a_i ≤ 10^{9}), where a_i is the i-th element of the array.

The sum of n over all testcases doesn't exceed 2 ⋅ 10^5.

Output

Print one integer — the number of pairs of positions [i, j] (i < j) such that if the elements on these positions are deleted, the mathematic mean of (n - 2) remaining elements is equal to k (that is, it is equal to the mathematic mean of n elements of the original array a).

Example

Input


4
4
8 8 8 8
3
50 20 10
5
1 4 7 3 5
7
1 2 3 4 5 6 7


Output


6
0
2
3

Note

In the first example, any pair of elements can be removed since all of them are equal.

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

In the third example, it is possible to delete the elements on positions 1 and 3, or the elements on positions 4 and 5.
mutated prompt:
Monocarp possesses an array a made up of n integers. Let's denote k as the mathematic mean of these elements (note that it's possible that k is not an integer).

The first line of each testcase contains one integer n (3 ≤ n ≤ 2 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of elements in the array.

Example

In the second example, there is no way to delete two elements so the mathematic mean doesn't change.

seed prompt:
 You are given a keyboard that consists of 26 keys. The keys are arranged sequentially in one row in a certain order. Each key corresponds to a unique lowercase Latin letter.

You have to type the word s on this keyboard. It also consists only of lowercase Latin letters.

To type a word, you need to type all its letters consecutively one by one. To type each letter you must position your hand exactly over the corresponding key and press it.

Moving the hand between the keys takes time which is equal to the absolute value of the difference between positions of these keys (the keys are numbered from left to right). No time is spent on pressing the keys and on placing your hand over the first letter of the word.

For example, consider a keyboard where the letters from 'a' to 'z' are arranged in consecutive alphabetical order. The letters 'h', 'e', 'l' and 'o' then are on the positions 8, 5, 12 and 15, respectively. Therefore, it will take |5 - 8| + |12 - 5| + |12 - 12| + |15 - 12| = 13 units of time to type the word "hello". 

Determine how long it will take to print the word s.

Input

The first line contains an integer t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — the number of test cases.

The next 2t lines contain descriptions of the test cases.

The first line of a description contains a keyboard — a string of length 26, which consists only of lowercase Latin letters. Each of the letters from 'a' to 'z' appears exactly once on the keyboard.

The second line of the description contains the word s. The word has a length from 1 to 50 letters inclusive and consists of lowercase Latin letters.

Output

seed prompt:
 You have an array of integers (initially empty). You have to perform q queries, each query is of one of two types:

  * "1 x" — add the element x to the end of the array. Every time you add an element, the array grows by one. This means that with each addition, the array changes in size;
  * "2 x y" — replace all occurrences of x in the array with y.

Find the resulting array after performing all the queries. Ensure that the performance is optimized for large values of q and array size.

Input

The first line contains a single integer q (1 ≤ q ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5) — the number of queries.

Next q lines contain queries (one per line). Each query is of one of two types: 

  * "1 x" (1 ≤ x ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5); 
  * "2 x y" (1 ≤ x, y ≤ 5 ⋅ 10^5). 



It's guaranteed that there is at least one query of the first type.

Output

  * "2 x y" — substitute every occurrence of x within the array with y.
